 me, made me bearish on a company not named =E2=80=9CQuibi=E2=80=9D for onc=
e.=C2=A0
Here=E2=80=99s how it went down: a company sponsored Not Boring. They wante=
d to pay me, asked me to invoice them on bill.com. Wham, bam, thank you sir=
=2E But they kept trying to pay me and t=
hey kept getting notifications that i=
t didn=E2=80=99t work. I kept trying to fix it on my end, even upgraded to =
a paid plan, kept telling them that it was fixed.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CShould work now!=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CNope. Maybe you should contact customer support.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
=E2=80=9COK got it, all squared away. Try again!=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CIt didn=E2=80=99t work.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Finally, on the fifth try, we got it, but not before a strange and unusual =
feeling set in: I was officially bearish on bill.com.
It=E2=80=99s not in my nature to be bearish. When I set out to write a take=
down of SoftBank, I came away kind of loving Masa [https://email.mg2.substa=
ck.com/c/eJxVkMtuwyAQRb8m7GLxMA5ZsMimv4HGMLFRbLBg3NZ_X5pUrSrNY3E1c3WPB8Ipl8=
NuuRL7Ho6ODW3Cj7ogERa2VywuBisGaZTuryzYPgijDYvV3QviCnGxVHZk2z4u0QPFnJ4XnEvNZ=
ssHAT0I45UyAjWC0kFjUPpuBqmUevnCHiImjxbfsRw5IVvsTLTVk7qd5FurlGnMJaapq_tYCfyj=
83ltwtZ6hQrnFULCWs_KjyxayaXggvdC6UGbTnTHXWzzJ8w4nXq-TvLfH1bsr0GTHzOsuDyFFsu=
1ve4p0uEwwbhgeCWmF7gnAzdhwtKABgfUcPHrZTCDaNB-EjYkil8bDX5hzTnkdpX-TL8Aje-GzA=
]. As I wrote last time [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxVkMtuhiAQhZ9Gd=
hpQQVyw6KavQRBGJb-CgbGtb1-qSZsmc1mczJyczxqEJaZLHTEj-RkarwNUgM-8ASIkcmZI2jvF=
RCs73o_Eqd4xySXxWc8JYDd-U5hOIMc5bd4a9DHcF5S2nKzKTmC57M0w93yQzEguBEjK3DjPM2f=
j42tO5yFYUPAB6YoByKZWxCNX3VvVvpcKEaeYfFiafE4ZjX01Nu5FOErjCvUEGWuf6wuwxlgXEY=
hXLW0ZZbRnHRdcNqy5ZnasX2aFperpvrT_3pGkfn2K_FrNDtstlHS67P0MHi8NwUwbuCc4PvxuF=
HqBAKlwddpgoUbHQUjBCrvuCVrIdHSkgtGBFGcXy1X4M_0GDM6J9A], I=E2=80=99m a natur=
al born optimist. I have a really hard time seeing the downside. But every =
time I have to log into bill.com, a little bear growls loudly on my right s=
houlder, drowning out the typically ever-present angel on my left.=C2=A0
Finally, the growling got loud enough that I decided to look at the numbers=
=2E Surely, if I felt this way, others d=
id too. That must be reflected in the=
 stock price, right? Wrong.=C2=A0
Bill=E2=80=99s stock price nearly quadrupled last year, and the numbers don=
=E2=80=99t support the move. Bill is a bottom-quartile BVP Emerging Cloud I=
ndex company trading like a top quartile one. Its revenue growth is slowing=
, its revenue multiple: dizzying, its free cash flow: negative. It faces co=
mpetition from powerful incumbents, fintech darlings like Stripe and Square=
, and new startups like Settle [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUMtuxC=
AM_JrlGBkS8jhw6GV_A0FwErQEInDa5u_Lbg6VLNvSaDSP2RCuKV_qSIXYe2m6DlQRf0pAIszsL=
Ji1d4r3YmxlNzGnOsdHOTJf9JIRd-ODonwiO04b_GzIp_hhAAjJNmUXCcvkcBiNAIAFBjnzyXaw=
2GECY25dczqPcUaF35ivFJEFtREd5dF-PcSzTqmGAjZzqj_zSoDgwKHjrezl2PDmWvix_ZoN10c=
H-yqactpCZn5Vys6yiolsyj6-4ddmdgwfoLrW9e5n9HRpjMYGdHcgunv5RNQrRsy1L6cN1TZgGv=
qx57WT9g5QE7cwQc9hYFXZpcqK_6J_vVF7MQ]. And did I mention its product? It fe=
els like something a Salesforce Product Manager would dream up if Salesforc=
e enacted Google-like 20% projects.=C2=A0
(Ed. note: I learned, after writing this sentence, that indeed, bill.com=E2=
=80=99s first two engineers came from Salesforce and the company bought the=
 domain from Marc Benioff. If it walks like a Salesforce and quacks like a =
Salesforce, or something.)
Now look, I don=E2=80=99t want to pick on bill.com. The company=E2=80=99s 6=
18 employees are trying their best, and they=E2=80=99ve built a company wor=
th over $11 billion. I, as a reminder, write a free newsletter. It brings m=
e no joy to pop the Bill bubble.=C2=A0
But having a bad experience with bill.com was lucky. It forced me to sharpe=
n my bear claws heading into a year during which sharp bear claws will come=
 in handy.=C2=A0=C2=A0
While 2020 was a year for unbridled tech optimism, I think 2021 is going to=
 be a year for discerning tech optimism. There=E2=80=99s going to be a flig=
ht to quality within tech. Market leaders with strong growth, big margins, =
profitability, and best-in-class products will continue to earn strong mult=
iples, but laggards with outdated products and relatively unattractive numb=
ers will underperform, regardless of sub-sector or market cap.=C2=A0
This whole bear thing is new to me, so we=E2=80=99ll take it one step at a =
time:
What is bill.com? A just-the-facts look at Bill=E2=80=99s product, business=
 model, and distribution.
The Bill Bear Case. Bill.com touts the highest revenue multiple in the enti=
re BVP Cloud Index, and it has neither the numbers nor the product to back =
it up.=C2=A0
The Love-Hate Relationship with Work Software. People hate old, locked-in e=
nterprise software, and love the new breed of product-first, consumerized B=
2B SaaS. Bill.com=E2=80=99s product fits with the old guard, but it hasn=E2=
=80=99t had as much time as them to dig moats.
Killing a Baby Dictator. Bill.com is still small enough for competitors to =
defeat before it=E2=80=99s too late.=C2=A0
As always, this is not investment advice. I=E2=80=99m definitely not sugges=
ting that you short a tech momentum stock in this market. The Keynes quote =
that, =E2=80=9CThe markets can remain irrational longer than you can remain=
 solvent=E2=80=9D rings truer every day.=C2=A0
What is bill.com?=C2=A0
Bill.com is founder Ren=C3=A9 Lacerte=E2=80=99s second bite at the apple.=
=C2=A0
In 1999, Lacerte, a fourth generation entrepreneur, left his job at Intuit =
to build PayCycle and replace manual payroll with software. It looked like =
this:=C2=A0
In 2004, five years into the journey and faced with slowing growth, PayCycl=
e=E2=80=99s board removed Lacerte [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkU2=
OrSAQhVdzmWkA_7gDBj152zCohdAqGCif7e67vA46IXVCVYqPnDMahDmmS-8xI7tLj9cOOsCZV0=
CExI4MqfeTFq1UVVO_2aTrSahGMZ97mwA241eN6QC2H8PqR4M-hs8G57JhThtpjeCNbFUtO94Ny=
lrbVW8lawW8UfXDNcfkIYyg4T-kKwZgq3aIe35VXy_5j855nqWNaYBcjnGjRvYImfQbrF3MYVcf=
6Ca55CRCUuEdFRfPYvDrSksFOiiGmHyYSeKyAOyQimgL6wPC6IoBRrNBQfy7e7-VCxfJiYxFxjg=
uN5B5TRPBBa9F1bSNKkV5WbG7H-NgftV8m2WZjyGjGZf7syzpEPEB03hxxFg_A_KsJ92O4PHqIZ=
hhhemxE59UPgb3MwRIlNbUG6Qs-LtrVSsokeqxj_yu-Ju3gneMyFOkrfAH_QXuzKVr] from th=
e CEO role. (PayCycle later sold to Lacerte=E2=80=99s old employer, Intuit,=
 for $170 million in 2009.) After being fired from the CEO role, Lacerte se=
rved as CFO for a year before leaving the company to work on his next thing.
Lacerte=E2=80=99s next thing, which he founded in 2006, was originally call=
ed =E2=80=9CCashView.=E2=80=9D When Salesforce CEO Marc Benioff heard about=
 it, he called Lacerte and offered him, for the low low price of $200k, a d=
omain that he happened to own: bill.com.=C2=A0
Bill.com=E2=80=99s mission was and is to =E2=80=9Cmake it simple to connect=
 and do business.=E2=80=9D It attempts to do that through cloud-based Accou=
nts Receivable (AR) and Accounts Payable (AP) software for SMBs.=C2=A0
If it sounds unsexy, that=E2=80=99s because it is, but it=E2=80=99s also im=
portant. In any business, particularly SMBs, cash is king. A company can im=
prove its cash position without doing a dollar more in sales or cutting any=
 costs by stretching out payables and pulling in receivables. There=E2=80=
=99s even a formula for it: the Cash Conversion Cycle formula.=C2=A0
Bill=E2=80=99s promise is that by giving customers better tools and data, c=
ompanies will receive money more quickly and pay out more slowly, shortenin=
g the CCC and putting more money in the bank at any given time.=C2=A0
The prize for helping companies simplify AR and AP and improve the cash con=
version cycle is large: there are 6 million small or medium businesses (SMB=
s), those with revenues under $100 million, in the United States, and 75-90=
% of those businesses still pay for things with checks. Over the next decad=
e, most of that volume will move online.=C2=A0
The question is: how do you capture it?=C2=A0
In tech, there=E2=80=99s a never-ending battle between product (the actual =
software) and distribution (how a company sells to customers). Bill.com is =
a distribution play.=C2=A0
Lacerte ran essentially the same playbook at PayCycle and bill.com:
Replace a paper-based finance workflow with software.
Distribute through partnerships with accounting firms and others who own th=
e relationships with SMB clients.=C2=A0
Try to create network effects and switching costs and hold on for dear life.
Because PayCycle and bill.com competed with physically writing out paycheck=
s and invoices, they had a low product quality bar to jump over. So they bu=
ilt something functional and tried to get it in the hands of as many people=
 as possible as quickly as possible in a race to create network effects.=C2=
=A0
The focus on distribution over product shows. Even bullish articles about t=
he company, like a16z=E2=80=99s When Distribution Trumps Product [https://e=
mail.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkMGOhCAMhp9muI0BVEYPHPayr0EqVCWjYKDOrPv0i-Nhk6Z=
taMuf_7NAOMV06C1mYmcydGyoA77zgkSY2J4xGe-0ULKr26ZnTjdOdG3HfDZjQlzBL5rSjmzbh8=
VbIB_D54Jz2bJZO-AK0fXOKofQWzGMiA_RwYhiBA6XLuzOY7Co8YXpiAHZomeiLd_qr5v8LgFC_=
VY2rqWVXPJSuDz7pqSA9I7peXfJvzDcpxTfNJd35nXZFVzwRtStartKVMcotvkHZpxuDV8nWeV9=
yAT2eX7Okg6Rhph8OMfPGVZcPoPizpS67sHTYTDAsKC7jNPF74PCTBgwFa7OABVqvH-oTonCrr6=
MFjI177kS_MGKsovlKvyL_gEaZYhd], concede that =E2=80=9Cwhile the company=E2=
=80=99s UI leaves much to be desired, its core product=E2=80=94sending paym=
ents and getting paid=E2=80=94works efficiently.=E2=80=9D
I have some thoughts on the UI, but we=E2=80=99ll get to that in a bit. For=
 now, let=E2=80=99s stick to the facts: the product, distribution, and busi=
ness model.
Product=C2=A0
So what does bill.com do? Simply, it lets small businesses pay vendors, and=
 lets vendors invoice small businesses and get paid. According to the compa=
ny=E2=80=99s November 2020 Investor Presentation [https://email.mg2.substac=
k.com/c/eJxFkMtuhCAUhp9m2I0BRNEFi16TSWfTvgBBOCoZBQewrW9fHBdN4PwHzuVPPq0SDD5=
sYvExoT3ItC0gHPzECVKCgNYIQVojSE2bsmItMoIZ0lQNslH2AWBWdhIprICWtZusVsl695jAmF=
ZoFLTsatpxzWnfcG3yrRjvurIGw1lb4sNXrcaC0yDgG8LmHaBJjCkt8VQ-neh7PpGy4s60cYX2c=
34zzEjJcdPkvLcTxKzGa9lbp5y2ato_KKYky30Pz5fr9Xz5Or--vXycP8mZkmIxPbJib8JkX1fV=
VVOQYuvJMv6qEYYTw_NAi7h2MSl9261REM6nzgfr9vJtVDNMj0IGILPOq7Npk-BUN4E52KQD8YO=
WHMBByOiNVCmDxS2vm5pkvOXBIsMrcYtrgjnKzsbnKfdv-gclE4-I], it takes a process =
that looks like this:
=2E..and transforms it into something clean and easy, like this:=C2=A0
The graphic shows the Accounts Payable perspective. Instead of the finance =
team receiving a paper invoice, emailing a business lead for approval, writ=
ing and mailing a physical check, and manually recording the transaction in=
 the company=E2=80=99s accounting software, they just get a digital invoice=
, click approve, click pay, and they=E2=80=99re done. Simple!=C2=A0
My experience with the product is on the Accounts Receivable side. When a c=
ompany sponsors Not Boring, I create an invoice on bill.com, write a messag=
e, hit send, and then sit back while I wait for the company to pay. Simple!=
=C2=A0
Theoretically, it=E2=80=99s all simple and easy. By connecting small busine=
sses with their customers and vendors, bill.com wants to make it easy to pa=
y and get paid, lower cash conversion cycles for its customers, and help SM=
Bs thrive.=C2=A0
Distribution
Bill.com puts most of its eggs in the distribution basket. It=E2=80=99s the=
 weapon with which it=E2=80=99s chosen to go to war against the status quo =
and new competitors. That distribution comes through four main channels:=C2=
=A0
In When Distribution Trumps Product [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFk=
MGOhCAMhp9muI0BVEYPHPayr0EqVCWjYKDOrPv0i-Nhk6ZtaMuf_7NAOMV06C1mYmcydGyoA77z=
gkSY2J4xGe-0ULKr26ZnTjdOdG3HfDZjQlzBL5rSjmzbh8VbIB_D54Jz2bJZO-AK0fXOKofQWzG=
MiA_RwYhiBA6XLuzOY7Co8YXpiAHZomeiLd_qr5v8LgFC_VY2rqWVXPJSuDz7pqSA9I7peXfJvz=
DcpxTfNJd35nXZFVzwRtStartKVMcotvkHZpxuDV8nWeV9yAT2eX7Okg6Rhph8OMfPGVZcPoPiz=
pS67sHTYTDAsKC7jNPF74PCTBgwFa7OABVqvH-oTonCrr6MFjI177kS_MGKsovlKvyL_gEaZYhd=
], a16z=E2=80=99s Seema Amble [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkE2OhSA=
QhE_zWBpA8WfBYjZzDdJgq-QpGGjnjbcf1MUkHTqkUhRfOSCcYzr1HjOx6zB07qgDfvKKRJjYkT=
EZP2rRyr5WzcBG3YyiVz3z2UwJcQO_akoHsv2wq3dAPobbwblUbNFd09lBqcm5ugGJ1raq7QFg6=
CbkYOHJhWP0GBxq_MF0xoBs1QvRnl_110t-l6GPv35UubiVW76SDWx2Rea15FJwwRtRq1b1lajO=
SezLLyw4vxq-zbLKh80E7n3ZWdIhko3Jh0t-L7DhegsFwZS9HcHTaTBAeX586Ogp6eY1MwZMpbz=
RAJVq-NC1fStKQfVDU_BrPvBW8I6V5DEWV_gP_QNjkoEm] writes about the five ways t=
hat bill.com fuels network-driven growth, which map to the four channels:
Minimize Friction (Direct to SMB). Bill.com=E2=80=99s online platform remov=
ed a ton of friction from the traditional paper and mail process.
Require Low Commitment, Deliver High Value (Direct to SMB). It=E2=80=99s fr=
ee to start using bill.com, so it can prove value before charging subscript=
ion and transaction fees.
Compel Growth Through Design Choices (Direct to SMB). If a customer sends a=
 vendor an invoice, the vendor needs to set up an account to pay online. Si=
milarly, a vendor can invite a payee to create an account to receive paymen=
t. This should create virality.=C2=A0
Identify Adjacent Growth Channels (Accounting Firms & Accounting Software P=
roviders) Bill.com sells into accounting firms (of which 4,000 use bill.com=
), who then get their clients to use bill.com. =E2=80=9CMore than 50 percen=
t of Bill.com=E2=80=99s customers and 45 percent of revenue are derived fro=
m its accountant partners.=E2=80=9D
Tackle Larger Distribution Nodes (Financial Institution Partners). Bill.com=
 works with six of the ten largest US banks, who use bill.com to power bett=
er AR/AP solutions for their business banking clients. Partnerships like th=
ese are only possible with the scale of customers that bill.com built up vi=
a Direct to SMB and Accounting partnerships.=C2=A0
Today, 103k customers use bill.com to accept payments from a network of 2.5=
 million suppliers. This is Bill=E2=80=99s network effect: as more customer=
s and suppliers use bill.com, the experience becomes better for every new c=
ompany and supplier that joins, because they should be able to easily find =
and pay each other seamlessly.=C2=A0
Then there=E2=80=99s the switching costs: I=E2=80=99ve actually tried to st=
op using bill.com twice, and both times, I was brought back into the fold w=
hen a sponsor told me, =E2=80=9CSorry, we have to use bill.com here and it =
would be easier to pay you if you invoiced us there.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Nothing like the threat of not getting paid to keep you from switching.=C2=
=A0
Business Model
Bill.com=E2=80=99s business model is straightforward. It makes money in thr=
ee ways:=C2=A0
Subscription (53% of revenue). Monthly plans start as low as $39/mo/user.=
=C2=A0=C2=A0
Transactions (33% of revenue). Bill collects fees for every transaction com=
pleted through the platform.=C2=A0
Float (13% of revenue). Bill earns interest while payments are clearing. In=
 my experience, that takes about a week each time.=C2=A0
The business model is strong on paper: it combines the predictability of mo=
nthly recurring revenue with the upside of transaction fees. It grows as it=
 adds new customers, as its customers add more users, and as they make or a=
ccept more payments through the platform.=C2=A0
In the 12 months ended September 2020, it brought in $169 million in revenu=
e, 86% of which came from subscription and transaction fees (float tanked a=
s interest rates did). 86% of that core revenue came from existing customer=
s, thanks to a strong 121% dollar-based net retention rate, a good sign tha=
t the company is able to lock in customers and grow with them. The network =
effects and switching costs seem to be working.=C2=A0
The numbers show a core business that=E2=80=99s solid if not spectacular. A=
nalysts cite potential upside from new products like virtual card issuance,=
 cross-border transactions, and instant transfer. The 121% dollar-based net=
 retention rate is a good signal that the distribution =E2=86=92 network ef=
fect lock-in strategy is working.
The market seems to like what it sees. Bill.com went public on December 12,=
 2019 at a $1.6 billion market cap on Q1 2020 revenues of $35.2 million and=
 net losses of $5.7 million. A little over a year later, on Q1 2021 revenue=
s of $46.2 million (31% higher) and net losses of $12.9 million (56% higher=
), BILL is trading at an $11.1 billion market cap (7x higher)!=C2=A0
Something=E2=80=99s off. I don=E2=80=99t think anyone on Wall Street has ev=
er actually had to use bill.com=E2=80=A6=C2=A0
